Problem Statement Key-Points¶

A bank's consumer credit department wants to update its decision-making process for credit scoring through Machine Learning and Deep Learning methods. Model's biases is a major consideration and the Equal Credit Opportunity must be respected. Specifically, the model is based on intrisically biased data.

Additionaly, recommendations and features importance must be provided for both for approved loans and rejected loans.

The goals are to:

  1. Perform customer analysis i.e., EDA
  2. Build an ML model that predicts the probability for a given customer to be granted a loan
  3. Interpretability and feature importances for both classes

I. Data Loading¶

  • Download the hmeq.csv database and load it into a DataFrame (pandas), marked df (pandas).
  • Display the database attributes and their number. What type are they (real, nominal or binary variables...)

  • Data Pre-Processing:

    • replace missing values with mode using df.fillna.
    • identify sensitive variables to eventually protect
    • identify over-representation or under-representation of categories
    • transform non-numeric variables into binary variables using pandas.get_dummies when applicable.
    • remove duplicates 'O.O'

  • Create a learning database and a test database (70\% learning 30\% test)

The loan distribution is leftly-skewed and rarely exceeds $25 000. The years at present job follows an almost uniform distribution with a high concentration of clients with less than 5 years of professional experience. The reason variables has two categories, improving home and paying current debts. The most common categories in job is "other" with 42% of total clients falling into that category. Most clients asking for loans to pay current debts have a higher risk of defaulting on their new loans. Having a higher property value is negatively correlated with the rate of defaulting. A lower mortgage amount is negatively correlated with the rate of defaulting.

General Description of the dataset¶

The DataFrame displays the first 5 rows of the dataset, for all 21 columns and a total of 5960 entries i.e., 5960 orders.

Each row corresponds to an loan request made by a client to the credit department. Each demand is anonymously and uniquely identified by an identification number.

Furthermore, the dataset provides the amount of loan approved, as well as the amount due on the existing mortgage, the current value of the property, the reason of the loan request, the client's occupation, the number of derogatory reports, the age of the oldest credit line in months, the number of recent credit inquiries, the number of existing credit lines as well as the debt-to-income ration.

Data Types and Missing Values¶

Overall, the categorical variables are stored as object before one-hot encoding and the remaining variables are float64 and int64. The missing values are imputed by the median for robusteness properties compared to the mean.

Self-employed clients are apparently more often accredited a loan than other professionals, despite having higher debt-to-income ratios, higher loan amounts as well as greater existing mortgages due.

1)Compute the disparate_impact(Y,S) function that takes two binary variables $\hat{Y}$ (or $Y$) , and $S$ such that:¶

$$¶

DI(\hat{Y},S)=\frac{P(\hat{Y}=1|S=0)}{P(\hat{Y}=1|S=1)} $$

In [19]:
def disparate_impact(Y,S):   #Fonction disparate_impact
    num=sum((Y==1)&(S==0))/sum((S==0))
    den=sum((Y==1)&(S==1))/sum((S==1))
    return num/den

def prediction(labels,pred):
    c=0 #Initialize count at 0
    lim = int(len(pred))
    for i in range(lim):
        if pred[i]!=labels[i]:
            c=c+1 #+1 to counter if prediction is different from label (for each value)
    score=100-float(c)/lim*100 #Compute Score
    return score

prediction(labels_lr,pred_lr)

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
lr=LogisticRegression(max_iter=300)
parameters = {
    "solver":['newton-cg','lbfgs','liblinear','sag','saga'],
    "multi_class":['auto','ovr','multinomial']}

score_opti_lr=lr_opti.best_score_

Here again, optimizing the parameters increases classification rates, at the cost of increasing disparate impact (except for logistic regression).

Removing the Self variable does not significantly alter the disparate impact and classification rates for the different classifiers. In fact, these two items of information remain very similar in both cases (with and without the White variable), which means that removing the Self variable from our X_train and X_test frame data does not correct the bias.

6) Compute the error ratio of the classifier¶

$$ ER(\hat{Y},S)=\frac{P(Y=1|\hat{Y}=1,S=0)}{P(Y=1|\hat{Y}=1,S=1)} $$
In [110]:
def error_ratio(Yhat,S):
    pr_0=sum((np.ravel(Y_test.values)==1)&(S==0)&(Yhat==1))/sum((S==0)&(Yhat==1))
    pr_1=sum((np.ravel(Y_test.values)==1)&(S==1)&(Yhat==1))/sum((S==1)&(Yhat==1))
    return pr_0/pr_1

We favor the XGBoost and the Random Forest Classifiers because they have the best trade-off of classification scores in terms of accuracy (the highest the better), disparate impact (the lowest the better) and error ratio (the lowest the better). One could further improve the performances by building a larger ensemble model with both the XGBoost and Random Forest Classifier. One interesting insight to this problem is the hidden bias built-in Self-employed clients for credit approval by the bank, even though they borrow more money than other professionals, with a have a debt-to-income ratio on average. Relying on XGBoost and Random Forest offers predictions that are more robust to slight changes in feature distributions and outliers than Decision Tree or KNN.

The most important features to consider are the debt-to-income ratio for both methods, the current value of the property and the number of delinquent credit lines. Overall, both classifiers have an accuracy score between 90 and 92%, and disparate impacts close to 0.5. Complexity and randomness associated with the method increases error ratio. And one always has to balance data predictability with model capability. In particular, stakeholders should rely on objective metrics of credit scoring such as debt-to-income ratio and try to avoid cognitive biases induced by the profession of a given client. For example, stakeholders could easily over-estimate the credit score of a self-entrepeneur when business cycles are favorable. But credits are long-term investment that cannot be assessed by short-term circumstances. That is why value property is also a good metric to assess one's capacity to pay its loan.

From a pratical stand-point, stakeholders could look at current and forecasted distributions of property values and debt-to-income ratio to score credit. To such extent, further analysis using micro and macro-economic and quantitative finance models could help link credit scores to inflation rates and the real-estate market. With that being said, the best classifiers in terms of accuracy connected to such endogenous parameters will always be more difficult to interpret, and prone to bias reproduction than simpler models. That is why the disparate impact and the error ratio need to be assessed along with credit score predictions.
